Step 1 — Put Taint on Node

Node protects itself.

Example:

kubectl taint nodes node-c env=prod:NoSchedule

Meaning:

“No pod allowed here unless tolerated.”

Step 2 — Add Toleration in Specific Pod

Only pods you WANT on that node get toleration.

tolerations:
- key: "env"
  operator: "Equal"
  value: "prod"
  effect: "NoSchedule"

Now this pod is allowed ✅

Other pods without toleration:

blocked ❌
But Important ⚡

Toleration alone does NOT guarantee pod goes there.

It only gives permission.

If you want pod specifically on that node/group:

Use ALSO:

nodeSelector:
  env: prod
Real Production Pattern 🔥
Node
kubectl label node node-c env=prod

kubectl taint node node-c env=prod:NoSchedule
Pod
spec:
  nodeSelector:
    env: prod

  tolerations:
  - key: "env"
    operator: "Equal"
    value: "prod"
    effect: "NoSchedule"
Simple Understanding 😄
Component	Job
Taint	Node says “stay away”
Toleration	Pod says “I have permission”
nodeSelector	Pod says “I want this node”

Together = strong isolation 🔥

Very common in Kubernetes and Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service production clusters.
